One of the closest globular clusters to Earth.

Sometimes classified as a nebula and sometimes a cluster of stars, this object is actually highlighting a portion of the Milik Way's disk which includes various objects like the open cluster of NGC 6603, two planetary nebulae and dark nebulosity of the Barnard 92 region.
Known since ancient times. First described by al-Sufi in 964 AD.

The Orion Nebula is a diffuse nebula—specifically an emission nebula—and is the brightest of its kind, where ultraviolet light from young, hot stars in the Trapezium Cluster ionizes the surrounding gas and makes it glow.
Also known as Seven Sisters. Visible to the naked eye.
Discovered by Charles Messier in 1772[b] while observing Biela's Comet
Discovered in 1773. Famous for its spiral structure.
Discovered in 1779. Ring-shaped planetary nebula.
M73 is technically not a true star cluster but a small asterism of four unrelated stars that only appear clustered together from our viewpoint.
M77 is one of the largest galaxies in the Messier catalog. It is located in the constellation Cetus at a distance of 45 million light-years from Earth.

M78 was discovered in 1780 by Charles Messier’s colleague Pierre Méchain. It is best seen in January. M78 can be found in binoculars and small telescopes, but telescopes 8 inches or larger will reveal more detail in the nebula.
Home to the first imaged black hole, M87*, discovered in 2019.
Edge-on spiral galaxy with a bright core and dark dust lane.
